-- ── Fredy ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Fredy is a free, open-source, self-hosted real estate search bot that continuously scrapes German property portals like ImmoScout24, Immowelt, and eBay Kleinanzeigen and instantly notifies users of new listings via Slack, Telegram, Discord, email, or ntfy.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source / Free$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$German$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Fredy Review 2026: Features, Pricing, and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Fredy review 2026: a free, self-hosted real estate scraper that alerts you to new German apartment listings. See features, setup, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Fredy, whose name is a backronym for 'Find Real Estate Damn Easy,' is a free, open-source, self-hosted application that automatically and repeatedly scrapes major German real estate listing platforms, including ImmoScout24, Immowelt, Immonet, eBay Kleinanzeigen, and WG-Gesucht, and pushes instant notifications whenever a new apartment, house, or flat matching a saved search appears. It is developed and maintained on GitHub under the orangecoding organization, associated with developer Christian Kellner, and is distributed under the Apache-2.0 open-source license. Unlike most of the commercial SaaS tools in this comparison set, Fredy is not a company or a funded startup; it is a community-maintained side project and self-hosted home-lab tool, similar in spirit to other popular self-hosted automation utilities in the Docker and Unraid ecosystem, where it is in fact packaged as a ready-to-run community app.

The core problem Fredy solves is specific to the notoriously competitive German rental and housing market, where desirable apartment listings, especially in cities like Berlin, Munich, and Hamburg, can receive dozens of applicants within minutes of being posted. Manually refreshing multiple listing portals throughout the day is impractical, and many portals do not offer fast, reliable, unified alerting across all the sites a renter or buyer might want to search simultaneously. Fredy addresses this by running as a persistent background service that polls multiple listing sources on a schedule defined by the user, de-duplicates results using a local database so the same listing is never reported twice, and pushes new matches out through whichever notification channel the user configures, including Slack, Telegram, Discord, email, or ntfy (a lightweight self-hosted push-notification service popular in the self-hosting community).

Technically, Fredy is built in JavaScript on Node.js (requiring Node.js 22 or later in current releases) and uses Puppeteer, a headless-Chrome browser automation library, to scrape listing sites that would otherwise block simple HTTP scraping through bot-detection mechanisms. To stay reliable against these anti-bot measures, the project has incorporated techniques such as browser fingerprint cloaking and, for at least one major portal, a reverse-engineered mobile API integration rather than scraping the public website directly. State is persisted in a local database to track which listings have already been seen and avoid duplicate alerts. The project ships as a Docker image (published to the GitHub Container Registry) and is designed to be run as a container with mounted volumes for its configuration and database files, which makes it straightforward to deploy on home servers, NAS devices, or self-hosting platforms like Unraid, where it is available as a community application. More recent releases have added a built-in MCP (Model Context Protocol) server, allowing Fredy's search and listing data to be queried by AI assistants and large language model tooling, reflecting the project's ongoing modernization.

Because Fredy is fully open source and self-hosted, there is no pricing model in the traditional sense: there are no subscription tiers, seat limits, or paid feature gates. The entire cost to run Fredy is whatever infrastructure the user already has or is willing to provision, typically a small always-on server, NAS, or Raspberry Pi-class device, plus the marginal resource cost of running a Node.js process and a headless browser. The GitHub repository has accumulated several hundred stars (commonly reported in the 500-plus range) and an active discussions and issues section, indicating a modest but engaged hobbyist and self-hosting community rather than mainstream commercial adoption.

Fredy's target audience is narrow and specific: individuals and families searching for rental or purchase housing in Germany who are comfortable running Docker containers or using a self-hosting platform, and who want an automated, always-on alerting edge in a fast-moving listing market. It is popular within the German-speaking self-hosting and r/selfhosted-style community, and is frequently mentioned alongside other home-lab automation tools rather than alongside commercial real estate SaaS products, since it has no ambition to be a consumer product with a polished onboarding flow, customer support, or a hosted version. There is no directly comparable commercial competitor targeting the same combination of multi-portal German listing aggregation and self-hosted, privacy-preserving automation; the closest adjacent tools are generic web-scraping and monitoring utilities (such as ChangeDetection.io) that users could in principle configure for the same purpose, and, on the commercial side, portal-native saved-search alert features offered directly by ImmoScout24 or Immowelt, which Fredy's users often find slower or less comprehensive since Fredy aggregates across multiple portals in one unified alert stream. Because Fredy is a solo or small-team maintained open-source project rather than a funded company, its long-term roadmap depends on continued volunteer maintenance and the cooperation, whether tacit or adversarial, of the listing portals whose anti-bot measures it must continually adapt to. The project has also been recognized by GitHub trend-tracking sites such as Trendshift, reflecting periodic spikes of interest whenever it is featured in self-hosting roundups, Unraid community app listings, or German-language technology blogs covering the country's competitive rental market.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '2315b74d-957e-4a28-a863-32fc0da75242';

