-- ── Freedcamp ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Freedcamp is a cloud-based project management and collaboration platform offering tasks, milestones, file storage, and a CRM, with a permanently free tier for unlimited users and low-cost paid plans for advanced features.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (Pro plan from $1.49/user/month annually)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2010, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$11-50 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Santa Barbara, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Freedcamp Review 2026: Features, Pricing, and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Freedcamp review 2026: a free project management tool with unlimited users. Compare pricing plans, features, pros, cons, and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Freedcamp is a cloud-based project management and team collaboration platform built around a genuinely usable, permanently free tier that supports an unlimited number of users, projects, tasks, and file storage. The company was founded in 2009-2010 in Santa Barbara, California, by Angel Grablev and Lofton Taylor, and remains a privately held, independently operated company rather than a venture-backed unicorn chasing enterprise contracts. Public employee estimates put the team at a small size, commonly cited in the range of roughly 6 to 50 people depending on the data source, which is consistent with Freedcamp's positioning as a lean, profitable software business rather than a large, heavily funded competitor to Asana, Monday.com, or ClickUp. This lean operating model is central to Freedcamp's value proposition: because the company does not need to fund an aggressive growth-at-all-costs strategy, it has been able to sustain one of the more generous free tiers in the project management category for well over a decade.

Freedcamp's core product covers the standard project management toolkit: task lists with subtasks and dependencies, milestones, a shared calendar, file storage, team discussions, time tracking, and password storage, all organized around projects that any number of collaborators can be invited into. Above the free tier, Freedcamp layers in more advanced functionality progressively across three paid tiers. The Pro tier adds email-in functionality (creating or updating tasks by emailing them in) and integrations with cloud storage providers like Google Drive, Dropbox, and OneDrive. The Business tier adds a project overview dashboard, an issue tracker, a wiki, an 'Invoices+' module, a built-in CRM, project copying, and custom reporting, which effectively turns Freedcamp from a pure task manager into a lightweight operations hub for small businesses that want basic CRM and invoicing without adopting a separate dedicated tool. The Enterprise tier adds white-label branding, single sign-on with SAML, daily data snapshots, private cloud hosting options, and a guaranteed under-one-business-day support response time.

Pricing is charged per user per month, with a meaningful discount for annual billing. As of 2026, the Free plan costs $0 and includes unlimited projects, tasks, storage, and users, with a 10MB single-file upload limit. The Pro plan costs $1.49 per user per month billed annually (or $2.49 per user per month billed monthly) and raises the file upload limit to 25MB while adding email-in and cloud storage integrations. The Business plan costs $7.49 per user per month billed annually (or $8.99 monthly), raises the file limit to 100MB, and unlocks the issue tracker, wiki, CRM, invoicing, and reporting features. The Enterprise plan costs $16.99 per user per month billed annually (or $19.99 monthly), raises the file limit to 250MB, and adds white labeling, SSO/SAML, daily snapshots, and private cloud hosting. Notably, Freedcamp does not charge for 'collaborator' style guest users on paid plans, which can meaningfully reduce costs for teams that work with a lot of external clients or contractors compared to competitors that charge per seat regardless of role.

Freedcamp's target audience skews toward budget-conscious small businesses, freelancers, nonprofits, startups, and teams that have outgrown spreadsheets and basic to-do apps but do not want or need the complexity and cost of enterprise-oriented platforms like Monday.com, Asana, or Wrike. Because collaborators remain free even on paid tiers, it is particularly attractive to agencies and consultancies that need to loop in many external clients into projects without paying per-client licensing fees. It is available as a web application as well as native iOS and Android mobile apps, and integrates with common cloud storage and calendar tools.

Competitively, Freedcamp sits in the same broad category as Asana, Trello, Monday.com, ClickUp, and Basecamp, but differentiates itself primarily on price and its unusually generous unlimited-user free tier; most competitors either cap free-tier users at a small number (Trello and Asana both limit free-tier collaborators) or do not offer a genuinely free unlimited-user option at all. The tradeoff for this affordability is a less polished, less heavily marketed interface than category leaders, a smaller integration marketplace, and fewer advanced automation or AI-assisted features than platforms like ClickUp or Monday.com have introduced in recent years. For teams and organizations, particularly smaller ones, nonprofits, and agencies, prioritizing cost control and straightforward project and task management over cutting-edge automation, Freedcamp remains a durable, well-established option that has survived and grown steadily since its 2010 founding while many venture-funded competitors have consolidated or pivoted. Freedcamp also maintains public changelog and status pages documenting steady, incremental feature releases over more than a decade, which is notable in a software category where many venture-funded competitors have been acquired, shut down, or substantially repriced during the same period. This longevity, combined with consistently positive reviews on platforms like Capterra and G2 for ease of use and value for money, has helped Freedcamp retain a loyal base of small business customers who prioritize stability and predictable pricing over the newest AI-driven features that larger competitors increasingly charge premium prices for.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'b5ae9c91-1ca9-4659-9b00-8decefc6bfbb';

