-- ── Freepbx ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$FreePBX is a free, open-source, web-based GUI for managing Asterisk-based phone systems, maintained and sponsored by Sangoma Technologies, powering over a million business phone system installations worldwide.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source / Free$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (core software); commercial modules and Sangoma appliances priced separately$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2004, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Ontario, Canada (Sangoma Technologies, project sponsor)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$FreePBX Review 2026: Features, Pricing, and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$FreePBX review 2026: the open-source Asterisk PBX GUI powering over a million phone systems. See features, pricing, pros, cons, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$FreePBX is an open-source, web-based graphical management interface for Asterisk, the widely used open-source telephony engine, and it is one of the most deployed business phone system platforms in the world, with more than a million reported installations. The project traces back to 2004, when a small company called Coalescent Systems built it under the name AMP (Asterisk Management Portal) to give Asterisk, which is otherwise configured through text-based configuration files, an accessible web GUI. The project was later renamed FreePBX and grew steadily through community contributions over the following decade. Ownership of the project changed hands twice: FreePBX was acquired by Schmooze Com Inc., a Wisconsin-based company, on February 22, 2013, and Schmooze was in turn acquired by Sangoma Technologies Corporation on January 2, 2015. Since that acquisition, Sangoma, a publicly traded telecommunications hardware and software company, has served as FreePBX's primary developer and commercial sponsor, while keeping the core software free and open source.

Architecturally, FreePBX is a PHP-based web application that sits on top of Asterisk and translates the underlying dialplan, extension, trunk, and routing configuration into a point-and-click administrative interface. The current major release, FreePBX 17, runs on PHP 8.2, uses Node.js on the front end for its interface libraries, and supports Asterisk versions 20 and 21. It is officially distributed for installation on Debian Linux via a bash-based installer script (sng_freepbx_debian_install), and Sangoma also offers a pre-built ISO distribution that wraps the same installer for users who want a turnkey server image rather than installing onto an existing Debian system. Security updates for FreePBX 17 are committed through at least December 2026. For hardware sizing, Sangoma's own guidance suggests that a small deployment handling up to about 20 concurrent calls can run comfortably on a modest server with roughly 4GB of RAM, a dual-core 2.0GHz-plus processor, and 80GB of storage, meaning FreePBX can run on relatively inexpensive hardware, a Raspberry Pi-class device, or a small cloud VPS instance.

On functionality, FreePBX provides the administrative layer for building a complete business phone system: extension and trunk (SIP provider) management, interactive voice response (IVR) menus, ring groups and hunt groups, call queues with agent management, voicemail with email delivery, call detail records and reporting, conference bridges, and a module framework that lets administrators install both free community modules and paid commercial modules for expanded functionality such as endpoint (phone) provisioning, advanced call recording, or fax-to-email. Sangoma has manufactured SIP desk phones designed to integrate tightly with FreePBX through its Endpoint Manager (EPM) module, and phones purchased directly from Sangoma include a lifetime EPM license as an incentive to stay within the Sangoma hardware ecosystem.

On pricing, the FreePBX core software itself is completely free to download, install, and use, and it is updated frequently by the open-source community and Sangoma's engineering team at no charge. Revenue for Sangoma comes instead from several adjacent layers: optional commercial modules sold through the FreePBX module marketplace (accessed via a 'Commercial License' section in the module updates page), Sangoma-manufactured SIP phones and PBX appliances pre-loaded with FreePBX, and PBXact, Sangoma's fully commercial, pre-bundled, professionally supported version of FreePBX aimed at businesses that want a turnkey system with a maintenance contract rather than a self-managed open-source deployment. None of these commercial add-ons are required to run a functional phone system on FreePBX; they exist as an optional upsell layer for businesses that want additional features or professional support.

FreePBX's target audience spans IT administrators and managed service providers deploying phone systems for small and mid-sized businesses, telecom hobbyists and home-lab users running a personal or small-office PBX, and larger organizations that use PBXact or Sangoma-supported FreePBX deployments when they want a supported, hardware-bundled version of the same software. It competes with other open-source and commercial PBX platforms including 3CX, Issabel (itself a fork descended from the same Asterisk-GUI lineage), and pure Asterisk deployments without a GUI, as well as with hosted cloud PBX and UCaaS providers like RingCentral and 8x8 for businesses that would rather not self-host telephony infrastructure at all. FreePBX's core differentiation is that it remains genuinely free and self-hostable at its core while still being backed by a well-resourced, publicly traded commercial sponsor in Sangoma, giving it a level of long-term stability and steady feature development that many purely community-run open-source projects lack, without forcing users into a subscription to get a working phone system. FreePBX's long operating history also means it has weathered a series of public security disclosures over the years, and Sangoma maintains a structured security-advisory and patching process for the platform, an important consideration for any internet-facing telephony system. The project's community forums and the Sangoma Knowledge Base function as the primary support channel for the free tier, supplemented by a network of certified resellers and consultants who offer paid installation and troubleshooting services for organizations that want professional help without committing to a full PBXact contract.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '2a33553b-3246-4484-92da-a333ec40b5e4';

