-- ── FreeScout ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$FreeScout is a free, open-source, self-hosted help desk and shared mailbox application built with PHP and Laravel, positioned as a privacy-friendly alternative to Zendesk and Help Scout with 50-plus optional paid modules.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source / Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (self-hosted); paid modules and managed hosting priced separately$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2018, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$and 30-plus additional languages$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$FreeScout Review 2026: Features, Pricing, and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$FreeScout review 2026: a free, self-hosted help desk alternative to Zendesk and Help Scout. See features, pricing, pros, cons, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$FreeScout is a free, open-source, self-hosted help desk and shared mailbox application built to give small businesses and support teams a genuine Zendesk or Help Scout alternative without recurring per-agent subscription fees. According to the project's own account of its origin, FreeScout was created in 2018 after Help Scout, the commercial product it is functionally modeled on, discontinued its free plan and forced all free accounts onto paid pricing, which the developer saw as an opening to build and release an open-source equivalent that any business could run on its own infrastructure permanently for free. The project is built with PHP on the Laravel framework and uses MySQL for data storage, making it deployable on relatively modest and inexpensive infrastructure, including shared PHP hosting in many cases, which lowers the technical barrier to self-hosting compared to help desk tools that require more complex application stacks.

Functionally, FreeScout replicates the core experience of a commercial shared-inbox help desk: incoming support emails are converted into tickets inside shared mailboxes, agents can be assigned, tickets merged or moved between mailboxes, canned responses used for common replies, and collision detection prevents two agents from replying to the same ticket simultaneously. There are no built-in limits on the number of agents, tickets, or mailboxes, which is a meaningful differentiator from commercial help desks that charge per agent seat, often making FreeScout dramatically cheaper at scale for support teams with many agents. The interface is mobile-friendly, and native iOS and Android apps are available for on-the-go ticket management. The core product supports more than 30 languages and includes accessibility features such as screen reader support. Push notifications, auto-replies, and Microsoft Exchange-based email authentication round out the base feature set.

Where FreeScout distinguishes itself most is its module ecosystem: more than 50 optional paid modules extend the free core with functionality such as live chat, a knowledge base, Slack, WhatsApp, Telegram, and Facebook Messenger integration, a lightweight built-in CRM, time tracking, workflow automation, SMS notifications, SAML-based single sign-on, and API and webhook access for custom integrations. This mirrors a WordPress-style plugin economy: the base application is free and open source under the AGPL-3.0 license, while a marketplace of third-party and first-party paid modules, most sold as low-cost one-time or modest subscription purchases rather than steep recurring per-agent fees, lets teams pay only for the specific advanced capabilities they actually need. This modular pricing model is fundamentally different from, and generally cheaper than, the flat per-agent-per-month pricing used by Zendesk, Freshdesk, Help Scout, and most other commercial help desk SaaS products.

On deployment and pricing specifics, the FreeScout core system is entirely free to download and self-host, with installation options including Docker, one-click installers through cPanel or Plesk via Softaculous, one-click deployment on platforms like Railway, Pikapods, or Zeabur, or fully manual installation on a standard PHP/MySQL server. For teams without in-house DevOps capacity who still want the cost savings of FreeScout's module-based pricing over per-agent SaaS fees, several third-party providers offer managed FreeScout hosting, with entry-level managed plans commonly starting around $9 per month, though this is not an official FreeScout product but a service offered by independent hosting providers in the ecosystem. The GitHub repository (freescout-help-desk/freescout) has accumulated roughly 4,300 stars, reflecting solid but niche adoption concentrated among self-hosting-savvy small businesses, agencies, and open-source-first organizations rather than mainstream enterprise support teams.

FreeScout's target audience is small and mid-sized businesses, startups, agencies, and open-source-focused organizations that want full control over their support data, need to avoid escalating per-agent SaaS costs as their support team grows, or operate in contexts where data residency and privacy requirements make a self-hosted tool preferable to a cloud SaaS help desk. It competes directly with Help Scout and Zendesk on functionality while competing on total cost of ownership rather than convenience, since self-hosting requires the team to manage its own server, backups, and updates. Other open-source help desk alternatives in the same space include Zammad and Tiledesk, though FreeScout is frequently cited as the closest and most polished open-source clone of the specific shared-inbox, conversational-ticketing user experience that Help Scout popularized, which is a meaningful part of its appeal to teams migrating away from Help Scout specifically. FreeScout also provides migration guidance aimed specifically at teams moving away from Help Scout, including documentation for importing existing mailboxes, conversations, and customer data, which has helped it build a reputation as a default landing spot for Help Scout users frustrated by pricing changes. The project maintains an active presence on GitHub, where issues and feature requests are triaged by the core maintainer and community contributors, and a companion marketplace site lists both official and third-party modules with their individual prices, screenshots, and compatibility notes so administrators can evaluate exactly which paid extensions are worth adding before committing to them. This transparent, itemized approach to pricing extensions stands in contrast to commercial help desks that bundle features into a small number of rigid tiers, giving FreeScout administrators finer-grained control over what they pay for as their support operation grows.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'd4008e96-5007-46e7-98c7-0f90f45c63fa';

